description: Within our own universe, in a sub-atomic realm, lie endless worlds of scientific magnificence, under the rule of an evil tyrant, Baron Karza. Can a small band of misfit aliens and one human put an end to his reign? Find out in issue #1. Classic space opera with a modern twist!Â  The Micronauts are back, BIG time! Acroyear, Baron Karza, Space Glider and Biotron return for an all new era of sci-fi excitement. On a distant planet, Earth-born Ryan Archer sits behind cold prison bars, and relays the tale of his arrival to a mysterious armored warrior. Can this rebel warrior help him? Will he ever see home again, or is he destined to remain there for life? More importantly is why the world's tyrant leader, Baron Karza, fears him. Join the cause this summer: the rebellion begins, June 2002!

description: Â It stood there in the depths of the jungle - eerie, stark, forbidding, its crumbling stones holding a look of cold menace. The natives of this remote corner of Burma called it Balila, but others called it the Black Pagoda... for black is the colour of death!

South Africans in Catolinas, French in Dewoitine fighters, British in Hurricanes... what a terrific bunch they were!

They fought among themselves, they scrapped among the Japs - and to crown it all they had a German saboteur and spy in their midst creating more havoc!
name: International Squadron

description:
When a German U-Boat was unlucky enough to become the target for a roving Spitfire, the crewmen were convinced they were doomed. And little wonder. Forced to abandon ship they were plagued by a ferocious storm, and the nearest land was miles away.

Or was it? Unknown to them, a British outpost manned by Royal Marines was only a short distance away. The Germans were in for a big surprise... but then, so were the Marines!

When it comes to living and fighting in the desert the Apache has no equal -and Juan Running Deer was a true Apache. His eagerness to be like his ancestors led him to North Africa with the British Army in 1942. Soon the battle-ground echoed to the ancient Apache war-cry, "Da' itsahh!" - "Unto Death!"
name: Private Apache

description: The Beyonder's Battleworld might seem a strange place to get new threads, but it's Spider-Man who becomes unraveled when his shape-changing costume attempts to darken his life as well as his fashion sense! But ridding himself of his riotous raiment proves an even greater mistake when its alien enmity bonds with mortal madness to form our hero's most dedicated decimator! Plus: the first appearances of Puma and the Rose! Mary Jane Watson's startling secret! And the debut of the battling...Bag-Man!? Guest-starring the Black Cat, the Fantastic Four and more! Collecting SECRET WARS #8; AMAZING SPIDER-MAN #252-259, #298-300 and #315-317; FANTASTIC FOUR #274; and WEB OF SPIDER-MAN #1; AMAZING SPIDER-MAN ANNUAL #10.
name: TPB

description: It's the incredible pulse pounding climax to the 8-issue miniseries as the mysterious alchemist known only as the Nameless makes his strongest bid yet to twist the Metal Men's technological souls to his will! Can Magnus and his Metal Men resist? Or are America's favorite knights of tomorrow to be reforged into the death-dealing machines of Earth's destruction?
name: Chapter Nineteen: A Matter of Time;

description:
Scrooge and co. search for a magical Finnish artifact which can make gold out of nothing! And the quest for it takes them to an adventure of the lifetime...

The story is based on Finnish mythology.

Made by Dona Rosa!

Also has other stories.
name: The Quest for Kalevala

description: Don Rosa spins a tale about the quest for the crown of the knights templar. It takes Scrooge, Donald and ducklings to places all over the world. For example, North pole and Haiti. There will be twists, dangers, jokes and epic secrets...revealed.
name: The Crown Of The Crusader Kings

description: Uncle Scrooge squares off against Magica in Marco Rota's "Pike Patrol," then Sly K. Switcheroo is in Romano Scarpa's "All You Need is Love." Also there's Beagle Boys and Gyro shorts, and the vintage Carl Barks tale from 1967 "The Cattle King" rounds things out.
